06617nam a22007095i 9780822390527DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20072007ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223905277 a10.1515/97808223905272doi  a(DE-B1597)553620  a(OCoLC)1224278607  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aD767b.U58 2007 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04aThe Unpredictability of the Past :bMemories of the Asia-Pacific War in U.S.-East Asian Relations /cMarc Gallicchio, Emily S. Rosenberg, Gilbert M. Joseph. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b7 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI Memory's Many Forms -- t1. Remembering Pearl Harbor before September 11, 2001 -- tII Policymakers and the Uses of Historical Memory -- t2. The First Revisionists: Bonner Fellers, Herbert Hoover, and Japan's Decision to Surrender -- t3. History and Memory in Postwar U.S.-Japanese Relations -- t4. Cold War Diplomacy and Memories of the Pacific War: A Comparison of the American and Japanese Cases -- tIII Making Memory Concrete: Museums, Monuments, and Memorials -- t5. Constructing a National Memory of War: War Museums in China, Japan, and the United States -- t6. The Enola Gay and Contested Public Memory -- t7. War Memories across the Pacific: Japanese Visitors at the Arizona Memorial -- tIV Transpacific Memories -- t8. Memory and the Lost Found Relationship between Black Americans and Japan 9. -- t9. Entangled Memories: China in American and Japanese Remembrances of World War II -- tConcluding Remarks -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Unpredictability of the Past, an international group of historians examines how collective memories of the Asia-Pacific War continue to affect relations among China, Japan, and the United States. The contributors are primarily concerned with the history of international relations broadly conceived to encompass not only governments but also nongovernmental groups and organizations that influence the interactions of peoples across the Pacific. Taken together, the essays provide a rich, multifaceted analysis of how the dynamic interplay between past and present is manifest in policymaking, popular culture, public commemorations, and other arenas.The contributors interpret mass media sources, museum displays, monuments, film, and literature, as well as the archival sources traditionally used by historians. They explore how American ideas about Japanese history shaped U.S. occupation policy following Japan's surrender in 1945, and how memories of the Asia-Pacific War influenced Washington and Tokyo policymakers' reactions to the postwar rise of Soviet power. They investigate topics from the resurgence of Pearl Harbor images in the U.S. media in the decade before September 11, 2001, to the role of Chinese war museums both within China and in Chinese-Japanese relations, and from the controversy over the Smithsonian Institution's Enola Gay exhibit to Japanese tourists' reactions to the USS Arizona memorial at Pearl Harbor. One contributor traces how a narrative commemorating African Americans' military service during World War II eclipsed the history of their significant early-twentieth-century appreciation of Japan as an ally in the fight against white supremacy. Another looks at the growing recognition and acknowledgment in both the United States and Japan of the Chinese dimension of World War II. By focusing on how memories of the Asia-Pacific War have been contested, imposed, resisted, distorted, and revised, The Unpredictability of the Past demonstrates the crucial role that interpretations of the past play in the present.Contributors. Marc Gallicchio, Waldo Heinrichs, Haruo Iguchi, Xiaohua Ma, Frank Ninkovich, Emily S. Rosenberg, Takuya Sasaki, Yujin Yaguchi, Daqing Yang  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCollective memory. 0aSino-Japanese War, 1894-1895. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zEast Asia. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zPacific Ocean. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aYang, Daqing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNinkovich, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallicchio, Marc, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIguchi, Haruo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIguchi, Haruo1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGallicchio, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSasaki, Takuya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinrichs, Waldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMa, Xiaohua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYaguchi, Yujin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390527zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390527423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390527.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles